{"name":"Weather Events","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Blizzard (Hazard 6)","type":"text","_id":"XcRYk9vvahAgtrU9","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival DC</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:25|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Requirements</strong> A blizzard can occur only during winter.</p><p><strong>Description</strong> A combination of heavy snowfall and wind reduces visibility and temperature significantly.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:21] (trained) to notice escalations in the weather or @Check[type:nature|dc:25] (expert) to correctly interpret the behavior of local wildlife.</p><p><strong>Routine (8+ hours)</strong> For the blizzard’s duration, visibility is reduced to such an extent that @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-kingmaker-tools.kingmaker-tools-weather-effects.qc5NAt3xu8sumqEh]{visual Perception checks have a –4 circumstance penalty}. Windstorm conditions (page 125) apply during a blizzard, and the regional temperature drops to severe cold. Once a blizzard starts, an unsheltered character takes [[/r 2d6]] cold damage every hour. During a blizzard, a @Check[type:survival|dc:25] check is enough to find or create shelter to avoid additional cold damage from exposure, but each attempt to do so takes 1 hour.</p><p>Once a blizzard ends, travel through the zone is treated as difficult terrain for a number of days equal to the number of flat checks that were required to end the blizzard.</p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Cold Snap (Hazard 1)","type":"text","_id":"mprUXhJvtqcQyQr7","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:16|traits:secret] (trained)</p><p><strong>Requirements</strong> A cold snap can occur at any time except during the summer.</p><p><strong>Description</strong> The temperature drops noticeably, becoming unusually cold for this time of year.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:nature|dc:19] (trained) or @Check[type:survival|dc:16] (trained) to realize there’s an imminent shift in weather.</p><p><strong>Routine (24+ hours)</strong> The temperature drops down to an unusually low level. During spring and autumn, the temperature shifts to mild cold. During winter, the temperature shifts to severe cold, during which unsheltered PCs take [[/r 1d6]] cold damage per hour. If a blizzard takes place during a cold snap, the blizzard’s temperature drops to extreme cold, during which unsheltered PCs take [[/r 2d6]] cold damage every 10 minutes.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Flash Flood (Hazard 7)","type":"text","_id":"8XUSo5x19YSSoFtt","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:27|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Requirements</strong> The PCs are in a hex that contains hills, mountains, or a river.</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Heavy rainfall upriver or deeper in the mountains causes a sudden rush of water to come cascading downstream or along an otherwise dry riverbed.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:21] (trained) to move to high ground before the flash flood hits.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hours)</strong> The rushing waters of the flood surge through the area with shocking speed. The PCs roll initiative with Perception or Survival checks; determine the flash flood’s initiative by rolling [[/r 1d20+17]]. On a PC’s turn, they can attempt to move out of the flood’s path. This could be as simple as taking Strides to get out of the way, or this could be complicated by having to succeed at a @Check[type:athletics|dc:25] check to climb to safety.</p><p>You can also complicate escape by having the width of the flood area be more significant, to an extent that even three Strides might not be enough to escape. On the flash flood’s turn, it attempts to Sweep Away any PCs who haven’t escaped its path. A character who is swept away can escape the flood by succeeding at a @Check[type:athletics|dc:25] check as a three-round Interact action to swim to shore or cling to an outcropping, tree, or other solid object; otherwise, the PC will continue to be Swept Away round after round.</p><p>Once the flood ends, the waters of the river left behind remain deep for several more hours or, at your discretion, even days.</p><p><strong>Sweep Away</strong> <span class=\"pf2-icon\">3</span> The flash flood sweeps away characters who haven’t escaped its path. Each character is carried 200 feet downriver (they can avoid this by succeeding at a @Check[type:athletics|dc:30] check to Swim) and takes [[/r 6d6]] bludgeoning damage (@Check[type:reflex|dc:25|basic:true]).</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Fog (Hazard 0)","type":"text","_id":"Tkno1g6Ocec0MqLy","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:16|traits:secret]</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Thick fog rolls in to obscure the landscape.</p><p><strong>Routine (2+ hours)</strong> As long as the dense fog persists,  @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-kingmaker-tools.kingmaker-tools-weather-effects.fznJUkfpRn2OOcBC]{visual Perception checks have a –2 circumstance penalty}. Fog causes creatures that are further than 15 feet away to be concealed, and it limits maximum visibility to 500 feet.</p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Hailstorm, Severe (Hazard 2)","type":"text","_id":"qA22W7YIBiQ8qfBs","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:18|traits:secret] (trained)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Pellets of frozen ice rain down on the region.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:18] (trained) or @Check[type:perception|dc:21|traits:secret] to realize that small showers of hail that have been dropping in the region will soon give way to severe hail.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hours)</strong> During a severe hailstorm, periodic flurries of hail measuring an inch or more in diameter buffet the area. Any character who doesn’t have shelter during a severe hailstorm takes [[/r 2d6]] bludgeoning damage (@Check[type:reflex|dc:18|basic:true]) over the course of the hour. A severe hailstorm also limits vision in the same manner as heavy downpour (see below).</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Heavy Downpour (Hazard 0)","type":"text","_id":"LsrmpnKQ4Mc86OKs","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:16|traits:secret]</p><p><strong>Description</strong> The clouds above darken, and a significant amount of precipitation unloads over the region.</p><p><strong>Routine (24+ hours)</strong> Rain or snow continues to fall all day, making those caught out in the elements cold and wet. As long as the heavy downpour lasts, @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-kingmaker-tools.kingmaker-tools-weather-effects.9xvn9jhwSpc7q44Y]{visual Perception checks take a –1 circumstance penalty}, causes creatures that are further than 100 feet away to be concealed, and cuts off all visibility at half a mile or more.</p><p>During a heavy downpour, other storms tend to be even more severe. The DC of skill checks made to survive, prepare, or endure the routine of a blizzard, severe hailstorm, supernatural storm, thunderstorm, or windstorm increase by +2 during heavy downpour. Rivers tend to rise during heavy downpours. Shallow points to cross rivers become too deep to ford and remain so for [[/r 1d4]] days after the event.</p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"Subsidence (Hazard 5+)","type":"text","_id":"Y9ihjoAiXpe8fI6D","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:22|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> With little warning, the ground itself suddenly gives way, be it a caused by a small avalanche, rockslide, mudslide, or the sudden opening of a sinkhole.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:perception|dc:22|traits:secret] to take a less dangerous path through the region.</p><p><strong>Routine</strong> A subsidence has no duration. Those who aren’t prepared when it occurs attempt a @Check[type:reflex|dc:22].</p><p><strong>Critical Success</strong> The character avoids the unexpected subsidence entirely.</p><p><strong>Success</strong> The character takes [[/r 4d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence.</p><p><strong>Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 8d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence. If the subsidence is a sinkhole, the character ends up at the bottom of a hole [[/r 1d6*5]] feet down and can clamber out with a successful @Check[type:athletics|dc:22]. If the subsidence is a mudslide, rockslide, or avalanche, the character is knocked prone and swept 200 feet away. </p><p><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 16d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence and is buried. Buried PCs are at risk of suffocation; see page 518 of the Core Rulebook for details on how a buried creature can be rescued. </p><h2><strong>Major Subsidence (Hazard 12)</strong></h2><p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:32|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> With little warning, the ground itself suddenly gives way, be it a caused by a small avalanche, rockslide, mudslide, or the sudden opening of a sinkhole.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:perception|dc:32|traits:secret] to take a less dangerous path through the region.</p><p><strong>Routine</strong> A subsidence has no duration. Those who aren’t prepared when it occurs attempt a @Check[type:reflex|dc:32].</p><p><strong>Critical Success</strong> The character avoids the unexpected subsidence entirely.</p><p><strong>Success</strong> The character takes [[/r 8d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence.</p><p><strong>Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 16d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence. If the subsidence is a sinkhole, the character ends up at the bottom of a hole [[/r 1d6*5]] feet down and can clamber out with a successful @Check[type:athletics|dc:32]. If the subsidence is a mudslide, rockslide, or avalanche, the character is knocked prone and swept 200 feet away. </p><p><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 32d6]] bludgeoning damage from the subsidence and is buried. Buried PCs are at risk of suffocation; see page 518 of the Core Rulebook for details on how a buried creature can be rescued. </p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":700000,"name":"Supernatural Storm (Hazard 6+)","type":"text","_id":"dyR8OatlsowoVgnO","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:25|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> What starts out as a heavy downpour or a windstorm takes a turn for the outlandish, as something strange begins raining down from the heavens above: bolts of fire, acid rain, or even something like a rain of frogs or shards of stained glass.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:nature|dc:25] (trained) or @Check[type:survival|dc:25] (trained) to find shelter in the region.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hours)</strong> Supernatural storms are the result of the growing influence of the First World over the region. When they occur, characters who aren’t in shelter take [[/r 4d8+18]] points of damage each hour (@Check[type:reflex|dc:25|basic:true]). The type of damage depends on the type of storm, as chosen by you. For example, acid rain would cause acid damage, while a rain of frogs would cause bludgeoning damage.</p><p><strong>Escalated Storm (Level +1)</strong> Supernatural storms can scale upward in level as you need to continue challenging the PCs. <a href=\"https://2e.aonprd.com/Rules.aspx?ID=1049\">Use the tables for building hazards on pages 75–76 of the Pathfinder Gamemastery Guide to set the escalated storm’s DCs</a>—it uses the high DCs for Survival and Prepare from Table 2–13 on page 75 of that book, and the damage value is the Simple Dmg value from Table 2–16 on page 76.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":800000,"name":"Thunderstorm (Hazard 7+)","type":"text","_id":"aUhuXJYIOy0H1GCY","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:27|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Dark clouds announce their arrival with distant peals of thunder and flashes of lightning.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:23] (trained) to minimize chances of being struck by lightning.</p><p><strong>Routine (8+ hours)</strong> A thunderstorm functions as a heavy downpour (page 123) during its duration, but with the added danger of being struck by lightning. If the PCs prepare for a thunderstorm, they can avoid lightning strikes and still travel by taking the Defend exploration activity (taking care to move carefully, staying low, and avoiding trees and the like rather than raising shields).</p><p>A PC who travels without taking this activity or doesn’t seek shelter must attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:6] each hour; on a failure, that PC is struck by lightning and takes [[/r 8d8]] electricity damage (@Check[type:reflex|dc:25|basic:true]).</p><h2>Thunderstorm (Hazard 13)</h2><p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:37|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Dark clouds announce their arrival with distant peals of thunder and flashes of lightning.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:32] (trained) to minimize chances of being struck by lightning.</p><p><strong>Routine (8+ hours)</strong> A thunderstorm functions as a heavy downpour (page 123) during its duration, but with the added danger of being struck by lightning. If the PCs prepare for a thunderstorm, they can avoid lightning strikes and still travel by taking the Defend exploration activity (taking care to move carefully, staying low, and avoiding trees and the like rather than raising shields).</p><p>A PC who travels without taking this activity or doesn’t seek shelter must attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:10] [[/r 1d4]] times each hour; on a failure, that PC is struck by lightning and takes [[/r 14d8]] electricity damage (@Check[type:reflex|dc:33|basic:true]).</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":900000,"name":"Tornado (Hazard 12+)","type":"text","_id":"52zyKfIV6HAjWnC0","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:27|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Requirements</strong> The PCs are in a hex that contains no significant hills or mountains.</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Strangely colored or ominously shaped clouds often presage the arrival of a distinctive funnel cloud’s arrival in the region.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:35] (master) to know how best to prepare for the tornado if no existing shelters are available.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hours)</strong> When a tornado touches down, the funnel cloud can wreak amazing damage. While the area affected by a tornado is relatively limited, predicting where the tornado will travel during its brief, destructive lifetime is difficult. Underground chambers can provide shelter from tornadoes, but characters who seek shelter above ground are still in danger. Each hour that a tornado persists in the area, attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:16] (for each PC sheltering above ground) or a @Check[type:flat|dc:6] (for each PC who isn’t sheltered at all). On a success, that PC is exposed to the tornado’s winds or its hurled debris and must attempt a @Check[type:reflex|dc:32].</p><p><strong>Critical Success</strong> The character avoids the tornado and its debris.</p><p><strong>Success</strong> The character takes [[/r 4d6]] bludgeoning and [[/r 4d6]] piercing damage from hurled debris, but they avoid further damage from that particular tornado for the remainder of the hour.</p><p><strong>Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 8d6]] bludgeoning and [[/r 8d6]] piercing damage from hurled debris, and they must save against the tornado’s effects again on the following round.</p><p><strong>Critical Failure</strong> As failure, but the character is also lifted into the air and hurled 120 feet in a random direction, taking an additional [[/r 60]] points of bludgeoning damage from the fall.</p><h2>Tornado Swarm (Hazard 17)</h2><p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:34|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Requirements</strong> The PCs are in a hex that contains no significant hills or mountains.</p><p><strong>Description</strong> Strangely colored or ominously shaped clouds often presage the arrival of a distinctive funnel cloud’s arrival in the region.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:43] (master) to know how best to prepare for the tornado if no existing shelters are available.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hours)</strong> When a tornado touches down, the funnel cloud can wreak amazing damage. While the area affected by a tornado is relatively limited, predicting where the tornado will travel during its brief, destructive lifetime is difficult. Underground chambers can provide shelter from tornadoes, but characters who seek shelter above ground are still in danger. Each hour that a tornado persists in the area, attempt 4 @Check[type:flat|dc:16] (for each PC sheltering above ground) or 4 @Check[type:flat|dc:6] (for each PC who isn’t sheltered at all). On a success, that PC is exposed to the tornado’s winds or its hurled debris and must attempt a @Check[type:reflex|dc:38].</p><p><strong>Critical Success</strong> The character avoids the tornado and its debris.</p><p><strong>Success</strong> The character takes [[/r 4d6]] bludgeoning and [[/r 4d6]] piercing damage from hurled debris, but they avoid further damage from that particular tornado for the remainder of the hour.</p><p><strong>Failure</strong> The character takes [[/r 8d6]] bludgeoning and [[/r 8d6]] piercing damage from hurled debris, and they must save against the tornado’s effects again on the following round.</p><p><strong>Critical Failure</strong> As failure, but the character is also lifted into the air and hurled 120 feet in a random direction, taking an additional [[/r 60]] points of bludgeoning damage from the fall.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1000000,"name":"Wildfire (Hazard 4+)","type":"text","_id":"3NdhHK8iKSzVq8mY","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:22|traits:secret] (trained)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> A fire spreads through the region, be it one accidentally started by a poorly maintained campfire, deliberate arson, a lightning strike, or from a supernatural source like a creature’s fiery breath or a fire spell being cast by a bandit in the region. Wildfires cannot  occur during heavy downpours or blizzards, and if such an event starts in the area, it brings an existing wildfire to an end.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:18] (trained) or @Check[type:perception|dc:25|traits:secret] to notice plumes of smoke or the tang of smoke in the air.</p><p><strong>Routine (1+ hour)</strong> An unsheltered character must succeed at a @Check[type:reflex|dc:21] or take [[/r 6d6]] fire damage ([[/r 12d6]] fire damage on a critical failure). If the character has sheltered in a temporary shelter or a flammable building, attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:16] each hour the fire  persists; on a failure, the fire consumes the shelter.</p><h2>Severe Wildfire (Hazard 10)</h2><p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:22|traits:secret] (trained)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> A fire spreads through the region, be it one accidentally started by a poorly maintained campfire, deliberate arson, a lightning strike, or from a supernatural source like a creature’s fiery breath or a fire spell being cast by a bandit in the region. Wildfires cannot  occur during heavy downpours or blizzards, and if such an event starts in the area, it brings an existing wildfire to an end.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:18] (trained) or @Check[type:perception|dc:25|traits:secret] to notice plumes of smoke or the tang of smoke in the air.</p><p><strong>Routine (8+ hour)</strong> An unsheltered character must succeed at a @Check[type:reflex|dc:29] or take [[/r 12d6]] fire damage ([[/r 24d6]] fire damage on a critical failure). If the character has sheltered in a temporary shelter or a flammable building, attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:11] each hour the fire  persists; on a failure, the fire consumes the shelter.</p><p>The heavy smoke in the area is thick enough to function as @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-kingmaker-tools.kingmaker-tools-weather-effects.fznJUkfpRn2OOcBC]{Fog} (page 123).</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":1100000,"name":"Windstorm (Hazard 1)","type":"text","_id":"wHlKOtYrRwcFubrk","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Survival</strong> @Check[type:survival|dc:19|traits:secret] (expert)</p><p><strong>Description</strong> High winds wreak havoc and disrupt travel, and they may even cause damage as trees or other objects are blown over.</p><p><strong>Prepare</strong> @Check[type:nature|dc:19] (expert) or @Check[type:survival|dc:16] to know how and where to find shelter from the upcoming storm. </p><p><strong>Routine (24+ hours)</strong> As long as the windstorm persists, the effects of wind on movement (page 517 of the Core Rulebook) are in effect. Overland travel in a windstorm is treated as if moving through difficult terrain. Once every 8 hours, attempt a @Check[type:flat|dc:18]; on a success, a  randomly chosen PC who isn’t sheltered is struck by debris.</p><p><strong>Debris Strike</strong> <span class=\"pf2-icon\">1</span> The targeted PC takes [[/r 2d6]] bludgeoning damage (@Check[type:reflex|dc:16|basic:true]).</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"ownership":{"default":0,"oxLvfZiIFxns2JLx":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.bulOFnIiyzwPMY7g"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"pf2e","systemVersion":"4.4.2","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1670861962325,"modifiedTime":1670865667390,"lastModifiedBy":"oxLvfZiIFxns2JLx"},"folder":null,"sort":0,"_id":"gCGQW4yrXFz4hwPa"}
